\title{Netlify Deploy}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Deploy web projects to Netlify using the Netlify CLI (`npx netlify`). Use when the user asks to deploy, host, publish, or link a site/repo on Netlify, including preview and production deploys.}

\subtree{
\title{Netlify Deployment Skill}
\p{Deploy web projects to Netlify using the Netlify CLI with intelligent detection of project configuration and deployment context.}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{This skill automates Netlify deployments by:}

\ul{
\li{Verifying Netlify CLI authentication}
\li{Detecting project configuration and framework}
\li{Linking to existing sites or creating new ones}
\li{Deploying to production or preview environments}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Netlify CLI}: Installed via npx (no global install required)}
\li{\strong{Authentication}: Netlify account with active login session}
\li{\strong{Project}: Valid web project in current directory}
\li{When sandboxing blocks the deployment network calls, rerun with \code{\startverb sandbox_permissions=require_escalated\stopverb}.}
\li{The deployment might take a few minutes. Use appropriate timeout values.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Authentication Pattern}
\p{The skill uses the \strong{pre-authenticated Netlify CLI} approach:}

\ol{
\li{Check authentication status with \code{\startverb npx netlify status\stopverb}}
\li{If not authenticated, guide user through \code{\startverb npx netlify login\stopverb}}
\li{Fail gracefully if authentication cannot be established}
}

\p{Authentication uses either:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Browser-based OAuth} (primary): \code{\startverb netlify login\stopverb} opens browser for authentication}
\li{\strong{API Key} (alternative): Set \code{\startverb NETLIFY_AUTH_TOKEN\stopverb} environment variable}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{1. Verify Netlify CLI Authentication}
\p{Check if the user is logged into Netlify:}

\pre{\startverb
npx netlify status
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Expected output patterns}:}

\ul{
\li{✅ Authenticated: Shows logged-in user email and site link status}
\li{❌ Not authenticated: "Not logged into any site" or authentication error}
}

\p{\strong{If not authenticated}, guide the user:}

\pre{\startverb
npx netlify login
\stopverb}

\p{This opens a browser window for OAuth authentication. Wait for user to complete login, then verify with \code{\startverb netlify status\stopverb} again.}

\p{\strong{Alternative: API Key authentication}}

\p{If browser authentication isn't available, users can set:}

\pre{\startverb
export NETLIFY_AUTH_TOKEN=your_token_here
\stopverb}

\p{Tokens can be generated at: https://app.netlify.com/user/applications#personal-access-tokens}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Detect Site Link Status}
\p{From \code{\startverb netlify status\stopverb} output, determine:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Linked}: Site already connected to Netlify (shows site name/URL)}
\li{\strong{Not linked}: Need to link or create site}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Link to Existing Site or Create New}
\p{\strong{If already linked} → Skip to step 4}

\p{\strong{If not linked}, attempt to link by Git remote:}

\pre{\startverb
# Check if project is Git-based
git remote show origin

# If Git-based, extract remote URL
# Format: https://github.com/username/repo or git@github.com:username/repo.git

# Try to link by Git remote
npx netlify link --git-remote-url <REMOTE_URL>
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{If link fails} (site doesn't exist on Netlify):}

\pre{\startverb
# Create new site interactively
npx netlify init
\stopverb}

\p{This guides user through:}

\ol{
\li{Choosing team/account}
\li{Setting site name}
\li{Configuring build settings}
\li{Creating netlify.toml if needed}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Verify Dependencies}
\p{Before deploying, ensure project dependencies are installed:}

\pre{\startverb
# For npm projects
npm install

# For other package managers, detect and use appropriate command
# yarn install, pnpm install, etc.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Deploy to Netlify}
\p{Choose deployment type based on context:}

\p{\strong{Preview/Draft Deploy} (default for existing sites):}

\pre{\startverb
npx netlify deploy
\stopverb}

\p{This creates a deploy preview with a unique URL for testing.}

\p{\strong{Production Deploy} (for new sites or explicit production deployments):}

\pre{\startverb
npx netlify deploy --prod
\stopverb}

\p{This deploys to the live production URL.}

\p{\strong{Deployment process}:}

\ol{
\li{CLI detects build settings (from netlify.toml or prompts user)}
\li{Builds the project locally}
\li{Uploads built assets to Netlify}
\li{Returns deployment URL}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. Report Results}
\p{After deployment, report to user:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Deploy URL}: Unique URL for this deployment}
\li{\strong{Site URL}: Production URL (if production deploy)}
\li{\strong{Deploy logs}: Link to Netlify dashboard for logs}
\li{\strong{Next steps}: Suggest \code{\startverb netlify open\stopverb} to view site or dashboard}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Handling netlify.toml}
\p{If a \code{\startverb netlify.toml\stopverb} file exists, the CLI uses it automatically. If not, the CLI will prompt for:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Build command}: e.g., \code{\startverb npm run build\stopverb}, \code{\startverb next build\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Publish directory}: e.g., \code{\startverb dist\stopverb}, \code{\startverb build\stopverb}, \code{\startverb .next\stopverb}}
}

\p{Common framework defaults:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Next.js}: build command \code{\startverb npm run build\stopverb}, publish \code{\startverb .next\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{React (Vite)}: build command \code{\startverb npm run build\stopverb}, publish \code{\startverb dist\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Static HTML}: no build command, publish current directory}
}

\p{The skill should detect framework from \code{\startverb package.json\stopverb} if possible and suggest appropriate settings.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example Full Workflow}
\pre{\startverb
# 1. Check authentication
npx netlify status

# If not authenticated:
npx netlify login

# 2. Link site (if needed)
# Try Git-based linking first
git remote show origin
npx netlify link --git-remote-url https://github.com/user/repo

# If no site exists, create new one:
npx netlify init

# 3. Install dependencies
npm install

# 4. Deploy (preview for testing)
npx netlify deploy

# 5. Deploy to production (when ready)
npx netlify deploy --prod
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Error Handling}
\p{Common issues and solutions:}

\p{\strong{"Not logged in"} → Run \code{\startverb npx netlify login\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{"No site linked"} → Run \code{\startverb npx netlify link\stopverb} or \code{\startverb npx netlify init\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{"Build failed"} → Check build command and publish directory in netlify.toml or CLI prompts → Verify dependencies are installed → Review build logs for specific errors}

\p{\strong{"Publish directory not found"} → Verify build command ran successfully → Check publish directory path is correct}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\subtree{
\title{Escalated Network Access}
\p{If deployment fails due to network issues (timeouts, DNS errors, connection resets), rerun the deploy with escalated permissions (use \code{\startverb sandbox_permissions=require_escalated\stopverb}). The deploy requires escalated network access when sandbox networking blocks outbound requests.}

\p{Example guidance to the user:}

\pre{\startverb
The deploy needs escalated network access to deploy to Netlify. I can rerun the command with escalated permissions—want me to proceed?
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Environment Variables}
\p{For secrets and configuration:}

\ol{
\li{Never commit secrets to Git}
\li{Set in Netlify dashboard: Site Settings → Environment Variables}
\li{Access in builds via \code{\startverb process.env.VARIABLE_NAME\stopverb}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tips}
\ul{
\li{Use \code{\startverb netlify deploy\stopverb} (no \code{\startverb --prod\stopverb}) first to test before production}
\li{Run \code{\startverb netlify open\stopverb} to view site in Netlify dashboard}
\li{Run \code{\startverb netlify logs\stopverb} to view function logs (if using Netlify Functions)}
\li{Use \code{\startverb netlify dev\stopverb} for local development with Netlify Functions}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Reference}
\ul{
\li{Netlify CLI Docs: https://docs.netlify.com/cli/get-started/}
\li{netlify.toml Reference: https://docs.netlify.com/configure-builds/file-based-configuration/}
}
}

